r reading through so many of the debates on this board (and others) it seems to me that the LDS have a very different view of God than other Christians. Also, it appears to me (and I could be wrong) that one of the big complaints that non-Christians have with Christians is the concept of who God is (i.e. the sending people straight to Hell if they don't believe).<br>
<br>
So, I thought I would mention what my understanding of the nature of God is. We, as LDS, believe that God is similar to any loving father, except that He has been perfected. We believe that He loves us. As a mother, I look at my children and I know how much I love them and I believe that God, as my Father in Heaven, loves me and my children with a perfect love, which exceeds the love I am capable of feeling. I believe that He sees our struggles and He is saddened by our pain and that he sees our joy and rejoices with us. (A little digression, we have struggles and bad things happen, according to my belief, because God does not take away the agency of other people. If someone wants to rob my house, just because I am a good person, God will not take away the choices of the robber. However, there will be consequences for all our choices, whether good consequences or bad consequences). Anyway, we, as members of the LDS church also do not believe that God, Christ, and the Holy Spirit are one being, all the same, big, small, can fit in your hand or fill the entire universe.... I have yet to meet someone who can really explain that to me that believes in the Trinity. We believe that God is the Father, that Jesus Christ is God's Son, literally, and that the Holy Spirit is separate but equally important. We believe that Christ is our elder brother, that we are his brothers and sisters (all children of God) and that when the Bible (OT) discusses sacrifices of the firstborn, well, there must be second born, thirdborn, etc. in spirit as well. <br>
<br>
Back to the nature of God... we do not believe that if you say the prayer, something like I accept Christ as my personal savior, yadda yadda... that we are instantly saved at that moment. We also don't believe that everyone who doesn't utter those words is going straight to Hell to burn for eternity. We believe that the concept of Heaven and Hell is merely one step in eternal progression. Those who have lived a good life, according to their knowledge, will first go to what we believe Christ was talking about on the cross... Paradise, a place where basically good spirits and those who have received and believed in the gospel of Jesus Christ will be (of course this is assuming that believing in Christ will make your works in accordance... we believe you are judged on your knowledge of right and wrong... It would be like giving a science major and an english major a test on quantum physics. You can't judge them equally when one has much more knowledge on the subject... does that make sense?) Those who did not know of Christ or accept him or who did know of him and who were not good people, did not live according to their knowledge of right and wrong, will go to a place called Spirit Prison, which can be equated with what most Christians call Hell. However, it is not fire and brimstone, burn you at the stake. It is a place of ignorance or lack of knowledge where we believe that everyone will have the opportunity to learn about Christ and His teachings and either accept what we believe was a gift, His atonement for sin, or reject it. After a period of time, those in both realms of the Spirit world will be judged. We believe that those who have a knowledge of Christs gospel will be judged more harshly than those who did not. We believe that at that point, unless you have had your faith turned to knowledge (which we believe Joseph Smith did when God and Christ appeared to him) and then denied that you *knew* Him (which Joseph Smith didn't - just to clarify), you will inherit a Kingdom of Glory. Therefore, according to our religion, anyone who has always been an athiest or who has never really had a testimony/belief that Jesus was truly the Christ would never end up in Hell (what we call Outer Darkness) which is where Satan dwells where there is no light and no glory. Everyone, except those who have had faith turned to knowledge and denied it, will inherit some glory. We believe then that there are 3 Kingdoms of Glory (like Heaven, where God dwells). There is the third which has the least glory (like the stars) for people who were basically not real great people... we believe that God loves them even if they commited crimes, etc but that they will not be rewarded with the same glory as those who lived a good life. Then there is the second (like the moon in brightness)  and the first (like the brightness of the sun) for the people who lived the best lives or who, according to their knowledge, lived their lives with integrity. Of course, we believe that God knows the hearts of all of us and that we will be judged fairly. I would assume that this means that a person who did not believe in God, but who believed it was good to do service and did service, who was charitable and kind, in spite of the fact that they may have persecuted for not believing in God, that they could inherit the highest kingdom and receive the highest glory, if they accepted the gift Christ gave in the spirit world. We also believe that every person will have a good chance to accept Christ, not the born again version of accept and be saved, but get to know him and know of his love. Some may never really get that chance until their time in the spirit world but they still get the chance. <br>
<br>
I know that for a/a's, it doesn't really matter but I wanted you to know, especially, that we do not see God as a stern, condemning being, but as a loving father who wants the best for us just as a mortal father would for his children. We see him as gentle and loving, yet bound by law, which is why he sent Jesus Christ to atone for our sins. He knew none of us would be perfect and He wanted us back with him. So, He found a way to satisfy the law (Christ paid the price for our shortcomings) and cut us a little slack... so we didn't have to be perfect to return home to Him. The irony in all this is that mainstream Christians say we aren't Christian because we don't believe in the harsh accept or burn philosophy and yet to me, the way we believe is much more in accordance to Christ's teachings of love and tolerance and they way you would expect someone who bears His name to behave. Or course, that is my opinion.<br>
<br>
Heather <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67@religiousdebate60574>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/5/03 4:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re; The nature of god</span><hr size=1> Why?<br>
