<br>
To me, this is simply further proof that man created god in his own image. For example, vengeful people believe in a vengeful god. People who hate homosexuals believe in a god that hates homosexual behavior, and so on. People look to religion to confirm the feelings and prejudices they already have. This has to be, because how could god's nature be knowable, and how can people presume to know what that nature is?<br>
<br>
Yes ST I agree that salvation theory makes no sense. Why would god create a method of salvation that was so convoluted and so incredibly difficult to believe in, but if we don't believe it we go to hell? Much more likely that Jesus's death on the cross was just how he happened to die, and his followers imbued it with &quot;meaning&quot; and added it to the dogma.<br>
<br>
DL <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> snowgirly</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(1/5/03 11:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=40.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Ok... Here goes </span><hr size=1> (...wondering what I got myself into)<br>
<br>
Well, I do believe that God created the law, basically that no unclean thing (or anyone who has sinned) could dwell in the presence of God, because He has *become* perfect (again, something that most Christians don't believe..). I believe that before we came to earth, there was a counsel/meeting in Heaven where God, our father, presented us with His plan, the law, ect.  much like a parent might meet with their children to discuss situations. In order for God's plan to work, someone had to be willing to sacrifice in order to satisfy the law. Two plans were presented. Lucifer (Satan) basically said send me and I will make sure that everyone returns no matter what... he wanted to take away our choices and take all the glory for his own. Christ said, no, send me. I will sacrifice myself to atone for their sins. Through Christ's sacrifice, we are all given our agency, the right to make our own decisions, to make mistakes, to learn right from wrong. Along with that comes the requirement that we repent when we do something that we know is wrong.  And Christ said that the glory would be God's. Which is basically why we thank God when we are blessed, we pray to him for guidance, and we love him. With Satan's plan, we would have no choice but to worship Satan. God wanted us to have the choice to believe or not believe, to worship or not to worship, to be good or to be evil. Through our choices we learn wisdom. God, as our father, wants us to learn and to grow personally, emotionally, spiritually. Satan's plan would not allow for that. But Christ's plan would. It gave us freedom. But freedom comes with responsibility (I'm sure I will be saying that to my kids when they are teens and want to take the car...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) The responsibility is that we are sorry when we do something wrong and that we try to improve ourselves. The reason God created a plan which required that there be a sacrifice was to teach us as well. In order for the sacrifice to work (to satisfy the law) Christ had to be perfect, which we believe He was. Through his life, his example, and his teachings, we learn how to pattern our lives, and we want to be like him because he was perfect and loved us enough to suffer and give his life for us, so that we could be imperfect (as we would be) and still be able to return to live with God.<br>
<br>
I believe that if the nature of God is that of a loving father, then his wife would be that of a loving mother. Whether or not God has more than one wife... I don't know that. Most religions don't believe that God has a wife or that we have a Mother in Heaven but if we are God's children and we believe that God is our father, it seems that ther should also be a mother. It goes along with our belief that families are eternal, that we remain a family after we die. That means that me and my dh will always be husband and wife and that eventually, we will have the chance to also create as God has.  <br>
<br>
As to why do I believe that this is the nature of God? Because I can't conceive of a God who is ruthless and mean, who would willing condemn many of His children to eternal damnation because they either had no chance to learn of Him (which was the case in many communist countries) or because they were presented with and believed something else. I can't conceive of a God who would only give one chance and if you miss it you are basically damned. I cannot conceive of a God who doesn't love me, as His child, at least equally as much as I love my own children. If my child makes a mistake, gets mad at me, etc, would I write either of them off and be done with them? Never in a million years. I would and will give my children every possible chance. I will forgive every time my daughter tells me she doesn't like me anymore. I will love my children in spite of choices they might make which are maybe not the best for them. That is how a parent is with a child. Loving, kind, forgiving, compassionate, and willing to do whatever possible to make sure that they are happy. And I believe that God is my father... not just some intangible, can't really describe him, being. I believe that He has a body (resurrected and perfect) and that we are created with bodies like his. Why else would the Bible say that we are created in His image if He was like many religions believe. We believe that if we were to see God, he would look like us, with arms, legs, eyes, a nose, ears, mouth, you get the picture. And I believed that when he looks at us, He looks at us with a love that runs as deep as my love for my child. That is why I believe that to be the nature of my God. I can't imagine Him being any other way. <br>
<br>
I realize that the burden of proof is with those of us who believe but I am not sure how you would ever prove something that is eternal with what I believe is the limited knowledge of man. If I had to have PROOF that there was a God, I would never believe in him. I don't have proof. No one does as far as empirical proof is concerned. But to me personally, I have the moments when I feel that something beyond me is helping me, or when I have the thought pop into my head to do something and had I not done it, I would have been harmed. I have feelings in me that for me, give me the faith that there is knowledge and reason beyond what man is capable of completely understanding but it doesn't mean it isn't there. I am not saying that it is the same for anyone else... but for me, that is how it is. And there is no proof of these things. If God had sent Satan, there would be proof and we would all have our choices taken away from us. Instead, we have our choices but we also have to go on faith, not proof. <br>
<br>
Also, science has often proved itself wrong. In order for science to improve and progress, it has to prove itself wrong and replace old theories with new knowlege. Beliefs about the universe have changed a lot from the world being flat, the sun revolving around the earth, etc. We are making advancements in science all the time. But science is still based on the knowledge of man.  It isn't possible to prove the things of God with the imperfect knowledge of Man. God gives us knowledge (I believe) a little at a time, not all at once, which is why there will always be questions in all realms that have yet to be answered. At least in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Now I need a nap<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Heather<br>
