<br>
Yet another difference between LDS and mainstream Christianity is that we don't see that the cross is what it was ALL about. What is really more important is what occurred before that. When Christ was in the Garden of Gethsemane and prayed to God, his Father, and there he suffered, cried, bled for our sins. He suffered what we would have suffered if he hadn't done it. He had to die and be resurrected so that we could all be resurrected. It didn't matter how he died, the only stipulation is that he had to consent to death. They didn't kill him on the cross. He commanded his spirit into God's hands and then he died.  But I just wanted to point out the difference... that we don't see the cross as &quot;what Jesus did&quot;. Rather, we see the atonement that took place in the Garden of Gethsemane as his offering to us. By the time they raised him up on that cross, he had already atoned for our sins. That is why Mormons do not wear the cross or display crosses on their buildings, temples, etc. The cross is not an icon or symbol of the Mormon church. It is a symbol of Christ's death. We don't celebrate Christ's death. We celebrate His life and his eternal life and what he did for us.  <br>
<br>
