<br>
For what reason, upon what basis, why do you believe any of this?  By what merit does this belief, or any of the xian ones, deserve the time and energy that is spent defending them?  In what way is this <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>True</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->?  Unless you can demonstrate it as valid, then it is no more deserving of belief than the idea that the world rests on the back of a turtle, or satan is god, or that if we don't sacrifice this chicken here the world will end tomorrow.  The unexamined life is not worth living (Socrates).  You might have a right to your belief, you might have a right to speak about it publicly, you are free to practice your religion, but that does NOT make it equally valid when tested against reality.  Believe all day you can levitate, then step off my porch roof and prove it.  Believe that the shaman's mystic talisman protects you from bullets, then shoot one at yourself.  Believe that harassing and condemning people to eternal damnation for not muttering the same mantra you do gets you into heaven, and show me how you know it.  Extrodinary claims call for equally extrordinary evidence.  <br>
<br>
I cannot speak for atheists, for they are not organized and only share the one common trait, lack of a belief in god.  However, I can speak for skeptics because they have very clear rules and structure.  This appears to be the pinion of DAG's problems in the arguments here.  That being that a skeptic accepts only what is proven.  (This is different from a sucker who accepts anything they are told or a synic who accepts nothing.)  It is the idea that we need to keep an open mind, but not so open our brains fall out (Sagan).  DAG is arguing for a disproof of something, but a skeptic does not start with a collection of beliefs and then demands the world prove them wrong. A skeptic starts from nothing and only adds those beliefs to their worldview as they are proven.  Logic has clear rules and gets equally applied to everything.<br>
<br>
I recommend going to the Skeptic Society website <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.skeptic.com/">www.skeptic.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> and ordering their Baloney Detection Kit.  It costs about $5 and contains a detailed explanation of most of the logical fallacies people encounter (Arguments from Authority, False dichotomy, etc.)  This is a secular work and makes no mentions of gods or belief structures, only the critical thinking tools needed to examine and evaluate merits of reasoned argumentation.  It runs about 12 pages long.  It does not delve into the whole mathematics of logic (All A is B, Some C is D. etc)  but it would certainly help people when they are about to stick their own feet in their mouth.<br>
<br>
DBC67<br>
