&gt;&gt;Because of religion you have countless murders, wars and oppressions. Racism, hatered and tribalism.&lt;&lt; <br>
<br>
People do things in the name of God that are horrible, but that mean that God is to blame? Assuming there is a God, which I believe there is, making people do these things you mention would go completely against His own plan. It would be Satan's way, not God's way. God makes no one do anything... people may use God as their excuse, but it does not make Him ultimately responsible.  People are accountable for their own actions... same reason we don't believe that men are punished for Adam's choices. <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;There is a difference between the justifiable confidence that springs from security in a position and the arrogance of believeing you cannot be challenged. I do not presume that I cannot be disproven. &lt;&lt; <br>
<br>
I was not saying that I could not be disproven. There are people all the time trying to show LDS people why they are wrong. I take the time to look at what they say and I am fairly confident that what they are saying simply isn't true. The problem here is like trying to compare apples and oranges because, as you said, you don't believe anything until it is proven to you, and I believe even without *proof*. I realize that you may find that naive and may say my brain is falling out of my head <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . That is ok. It isn't that I don't think I can be challenged. I come here right? But, just as I will never convince you without scientific proof, you will not convince me that without scientific proof, it must not exist. As I said before, there are many proofs which have not in the past been able to be proven, and many things now that are still not &quot;provable&quot; but that doesn't mean that they don't exist or are false.  Therefore, we are at a stand still on this issue. <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;I would dearly love to think I can see my mom again, that the girl who killed herself in high school will tell me why she did it, that my dad will have his leg again and get to chase me as we did when I was a kid, that my time with my wife will never end, that I can watch my kids, grandkids, greatgrandkids all grow up and have families. &lt;&lt; <br>
<br>
In that case, I hope I am right! <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;How then to distinguish between competing beliefs? &lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
The funny thing about you asking that, is that very question is what led Joseph Smith to a grove of trees to ask God which church he should join... He says he then saw God and Jesus Christ and was given direction from them. Does he have proof? Nope. Only his word. So, if there is no God, he was a liar and a fraud and we have all been duped. If he was not lying, then there is a God. <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;I say that if something can't be proven it shouldn't be treated as true&lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
So, if you had lived in the 1960s and you had slept with a girl who got pregnant and she had also been with someone else at the same time and you and the other guy both had the same blood type, even if that child looked just like you, would you default to there being no chance of it being yours because you can't prove that it is? Or if someone were to commit a crime against your family and there were clues that led you to believe you knew who did it, would you automatically assume that that person couldn't have done it because there is no absolute proof? Do you really think that everything that can't be &quot;proven&quot; is automatically false? <br>
<br>
I wasn't calling you arrogant, per se, only that when you are unwilling to see that there are people out there who may reason through things differently than you, you think that they are idiots. The thing I thought was arrogant is believing that your way of determining truth is the only acceptable way. It may be the only way for you but that shouldn't completely discredit other people because they perceive things different than you do.<br>
<br>
Anyway... off to my mom's for dinner... Check back later.<br>
<br>
Heather<br>
<br>
ps.... DBC, I hope you know that I respect you and your beliefs, reasoning, etc. I am not trying to tell you that you are wrong or change your thinking. I just expect that you will respect that I can be a pretty intelligent person and not reason things the way you do. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
